summary: The image depicts a study involving recombinant viruses produced in insect cells using a specific media composition containing 10% fetal bovine serum (FBS) and 2 mL/L sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS). The study involves the harvesting of the viruses from the cell culture, followed by the collection of hemolymph samples from infected animals. These samples were subjected to various analyses, including alkaline phosphatase, Western blotting with anti-rabbit and anti-mouse antibodies, and mass spectrometry. The results indicated that the recombinant viruses produced in the insect cells contained a significant amount of polyethylene glycol (PEG) and were successfully injected into animals. Additionally, the study found that the infected animals produced large amounts of antibodies against the virus.
